President Barack Obama has announced that $2 billion in funding will be allocated to state and local law enforcement and criminal justice assistance through the Edward Byrne Justice Assistance Grant (JAG) Program. The funds will be used to hire more law enforcement officers, support drug and gang task forces, fund crime prevention programs, and improve justice information sharing initiatives. The allocation of grants is based on population and violent crime statistics. The funding will also help retain police officers who would otherwise be laid off due to budget cuts. Various cities and states have outlined their plans for using the funds, such as upgrading records management systems, hiring crime analysts, and enhancing radio telecommunications infrastructure. The funds will also be used for violence reduction efforts, gang prevention, drug enforcement, and community-based treatment services. Additionally, the funding will support the creation of jobs in the criminal justice sector and provide resources for states and local communities.